The seizure of the shipment from Malawi bound for the Far East was the largest since a 1989 international convention banning the ivory trade took effect and represented ivory from 3,000 to 6,500 elephants.
Kenya and Mali are proposing an international ban on trade in ivory arguing that it was causing poaching of its elephants.
The West and East African nations argued that allowing any trade in ivory would increase elephant poaching.
Trading ivory was banned under the 1989 Convention of International Trade in Endangered Species to curb the slaughter of elephants in Africa.
